You could get the BBC to add the appropriate headers.

I am not sure what language they are using but if you send them the PHP snippet below and explain that the HTTP headers have to be set *exactly* like this for the request to get though they should understand.

Or simply send them this line:

wget --header "Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml" --user-agent="Mozilla/5.0 (Ubuntu; X11; Linux x86_64; rv:8.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/8.0" http://www.london2012.com/data/bigscreenrss.xml

OTOH we possible don't want to be so strict re. headers as it may limit the ability of search ending spiders to crawl the site (although I imagine SiteShield - which I think is the root of the issue here, although not 100% sure - lets though the main ones or else we wouldnt' be appearing in Google s search index).

<?php
	$url = 'http://www.london2012.com/data/bigscreenrss.xml';
	$opts = array(
		'http' => array(
			'method' => "GET",
			'user_agent' => "Mozilla/5.0 (Ubuntu; X11; Linux x86_64; rv:8.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/8.0",
			'header' => "Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml"
		)
	);
	$context = stream_context_create($opts);
	$eventXML = file_get_contents($url, false, $context);
	if ($eventXML != false) {
		echo $eventXML;
	} else {
		echo "error calling endpoint";
	}
?>

Tom, I think this is what you probably need to send them.. 

btw. If they are using a pre-built/existing application to read the RSS feed (and hence the headers can't be changed) then you'll need BT to relax the restrictions at the firewall (and the email below should make sense to them).

